segments.text: land use, as I was saying, Project Ag updating all the land use, Jonathan had decided that he wanted to move into the area what we would refer to as developing planning areas for the city and sector planning, and then assigning various personnel as area planners to work under the senior planner in charge of advanced planning at that time.
Who was that?
That was Bill Pearson.
And it took a little time to get started.
It was mainly set up after what had been happening in Fort Worth.
And I don't recall the date, but during this period, it also brought down from Fort Worth Emilio Once-DeVise, who became our senior planner.
And of course, as you know, Emilio is now back with the city of Fort Worth again.
So things have a way of making a circle.

During that interim of trying to set up the sector planning at that time, one of the new programs the federal government was sponsoring was the Community Renewal Program under the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
And of course, the Community Renewal Program had become the planning forerunner to
what would ultimately hope to be the passing of an urban renewal referendum, which never did happen.
And when the Community Renewal Program was set up, they were located at some administrative offices situated in Washington Park Zoo, which was subject of many jokes.
And Mr. Bill Adams, the Assistant Director of Planning under Jonathan,
took a leave of absence from that position to become the director of the community road program.
And of course, Mr. Adams brought in Kern Ewing as his assistant director.
And Kern is the person, the reason I mention him, he is the person who eventually caused my relocation to the city of Corpus Christi.
If everyone recalls, community road programs were primarily set up for funding on two to three year basis.
And as the CRP, as it's known, was about to close down in the city of El Paso, Kern had accepted a job to head up the Community Rule Program for the city of Corpus Christi.
And I believe that occurred in 1971.
And after about two years with the program, Kern, basically the program, the Community Rule Program,
in Corpus was first to set up a data bank for both land uses and other kinds of socioeconomic information to do an economic study of the city of Corpus Christi.
And from there, it was intended to lead into identification of the most severely blighted areas, areas which would be identified as future urban renewal areas.
At about that time, so the emphasis of the community renewal programs, as it had been with many other CRPs across the state, was the accumulation of socioeconomic type of data.
Now, if I can regress backwards, under Jonathan Cunningham, Jonathan Cunningham, in my opinion, was a traditionalist type of planner.
He was very physical planning oriented, and not only that, he was a very good manipulator in terms of working his projects

his projects and the various political processes with tremendous success, never taking credit primarily for the projects that were completed as his own, but somehow convincing other people within the community leadership that this was their idea and that they needed to follow through with it.
Like the mayor and so forth.
Like the mayor, your city council members are maybe one of the more affluent persons in some sort of community-wide organization.
People who would have the leadership ability and the influence to move certain things.
This must have made Jonathan a rather powerful person in government.
For the time that I was in El Paso, Jonathan Cunningham, as I shortly found out, was in conjunction with the director of public works, George Deiter.
Those two men were the most powerful.
How do you spell his name?
It's D-I-E-T-E-R. George Deiter and Jonathan were basically the runners.
They ran the city.
There wasn't anything that the council would do unless they
unless Mr. Dieter and Mr. Cunningham had given their blessing to the project.
And I don't recall how many years Jonathan was with El Paso, but I know it was over 30 years.
And it's just amazing for a director of planning to develop that kind of power from his position and maintain it.
over that length of period.
And he used it wisely.
There's a lot of related stories about Jonathan and how he ended up winning the budget wars as everyone went to the city council.
You have to remember that the city of El Paso was and still is a strong mayor form of government.
former council, former government.
They had tried to attempt to change it over to a city manager type, but they as yet not succeeded.

And in lieu of not having an officially appointed head of city government to manage the city's businesses as any other professional businessman would do, John Cunningham and George Dieter assumed that role.
And it became very effective.

I think John's demise as far as his power base was concerned began occurring with the retirement of George Deeder from his office and also the realization on the part of some politicians who I have known personally feeling that Mr. Cunningham had taken what had once been a very small department of planning and built it into a very powerful organization utilizing

the advantages of grants available from the federal government, including such programs as you recall, open space, urban beautification, et cetera, your 701 planning, community renewal planning, your relocation.
And he just assumed control over all these projects and just expanded them and expanded the staff where that
that one way or another anything that was done in the city of El Paso had to be brought back through the Department of Planning.
That's the way it ought to be.
But it was good.
At the same time, Jonathan Cullingham was the single person in charge of that entire process and it made him very powerful and the politicians themselves were afraid of that.

And although I had since departed, just from what I had read and heard from my colleagues back in El Paso, slowly but surely the politicians began to break down Mr. Cunningham's power base, splitting out a lot of the grants activities into other departments, such as the Community Development Bank grants, a lot of grants.
which are very significant in terms of total dollars and impact on the community for physical improvements.
But anyway, this is one of the amazing things about John.
John had always been the type of professional planner with a management skill that tended to elevate his people that he was trying to teach.
And for the most part, at the time I started, I was not even aware.
of professional planning schools, etc., or never even thought of attending one.
I had never even thought of staying on with the Department of Planning for more than one year.
I had always intended to return to law school to finish that up.
But I became very, so involved in planning and I enjoyed it so much, I just couldn't think of a better way to continue.
You know, we could always look at

the the money side of it and it was very apparent that you wouldn't get rich being a public service planner for any city but there were other kinds of benefits that that you enjoyed and other than civil service protection but the fact that you were actually having some impact on the community and how it was going to look and it carried with it a lot of respect and and as you've moved further up the ladder a lot of responsibility

After the community renewal program in the city of Corpus Christi had gotten well underway after those first two years, they had, for the most part, completed the collection of data that they needed, both demographic and socioeconomic.
And they had also divided the city up into planning areas.
So they could aggregate their data for planning areas and set up a land use data bank.
And they had done a condition of housing
condition of structure survey city-wide, and they were ready to move into some more physical aspects of planning.

And at that time, Kern Ewing had written me a letter and followed up a phone call one day asking if I would be interested in coming down here and being, starting as a planner one, coming out here and working on planning.
I did fail to mention that as the community renewal program in El Paso was beginning to fade out, phase out,

lot of the personnel that they had there on the program have been finding other jobs and rightfully so they they you know they they knew that the program only had several months to a wife left into a budgetary life anyway and i was temporarily reassigned from the downtown planning offices to the washington zoo to assist kern ewing and bill adams and a couple other staff able to finish off
to wrap up the CRP.

And our program there at that time, the wrap-up was doing, on a very small scale, neighborhood plans for each one of the, I think it was 13 to 14 neighborhoods that we identified as needing, in dire need of some type of urban renewal.
And which all these same reports were published in some volumes.
These are the volumes up here, a culmination of that entire project.
There's five volumes there.
One thing you can never change charts or say about, one of the things you can always say about the federal government is they've never been lacking on paperwork.
They're very impressive looking.
But we had them out there.
One of the questions that comes to mind is that in terms of Corpus Christi's community renewal effort,

In view of the fact that Corpus Christi never did act upon the urban renewal aspects of the original Bartholomew plan, that must have suggested something in regard to community attitudes toward potential community renewal efforts.
And I'm just wondering if that came to pass in the CRP program for Corpus Christi.
Was it successful, do you think?
It was never.

I think the efforts of the Community Renewal Program, Corpus Christi, were very successful, but it didn't, not in having an immediate impact on the community or in convincing the community that we needed an urban renewal referendum and urban renewal agency.
It didn't have that kind of immediate impact.
I think in the long run, the work that the staff members of CRP did
had a lot of impact in providing the information that we as planners and the managerial staff needed to make decisions.
And so I can't honestly say whether or not the total dollars spent in the community renewal program effort could be measured against its immediate impact if it would be worth it.
That's really hard to say.

But I can say, I think, very honestly, that the kind of work that was done with CRP, the fact that we, even though I'm more of a physical type of planner and a provisor of John Cunningham, I think one of the things I'd like to detail for you, and this is, in my opinion, my observation,
the emphasis, the planning programs here in this city, this community of Corpus Christi, has taken over the last 10 years.
And the changes that I have observed, drastic changes in the kinds of planning work that we do as a department.
I'll back up a little bit.
I joined the staff, community renewal program staff, March 19, 1973.
So from that date, this March 19th, 1983, I had been here 10 years.
I came in for the sole purpose of developing for Kern Ewing, who was the director, and Leonard Jameson was assistant director, a comprehensive land use plan for the city of Corpus Christi.
All the other work that goes into a comprehensive plan had, for the most part,
been studied and detailed and information was available.
I was talking about the socio-economic information, the community facilities, you know, et cetera.
But they didn't have the total land use plan.
I think it's in- Kern Ewing was planning director.
Kern Ewing was the director.
That's a good point.
Kern Ewing was the director of the Community Renewal Program.
The Community Renewal Program was a division of the Department of Urban Development, which was under
a director by the name of Ernest Briones, now our deputy city manager.
Well, let me say something about that organization.

It was my understanding that at the time community rural program monies were being made available to urbanized areas, that Corpus, as it was in El Paso and many other cities, was invited to apply, and the money, based on the application,
was granted to the city.
Mr. Anderson, being the department head for the Department of Planning, was responsible for making sure that application was put together.
Mr. Earl Gadds, Mr. Anderson's senior planner at that time, prepared the application.
For the reasons I'm really hazy about,

Mr. Goetz did not desire to be the acting director of the community program in the same manner that Mr. Bill Adams in El Paso took a temporary leave of absence from his assistant director job and became the director of CRP.
And because there was nobody on staff at the time that would have the time to direct these CRP activities, research activities, the then city manager, Mr. Marvin Townsend,
turned the responsibilities over to Mr. Ernest Briones, who had formerly been a health department employee.
But Mr. Briones had, in my opinion, a lot of administrative skills, very good management skills.
When Kern was brought in, basically back in 71, the first thing he did was put together a staff, qualified individuals, not of what I would characterize as a planning type,
none of which came from Texas A&M University, several who came from the LBJ School of Public Affairs.
Most of them had economic and sociological type of undergraduate work and graduate work behind them.
And that program was, in my opinion, a beginning of a transition from an emphasis on physical planning, short-range type of planning that

that moved into more of the social economic type of planning looking at some of the human needs of the community as opposed to the physical needs such as street improvements water sewer extensions new utilities etc and we had over the years i can recall you know we had gone through so many different kinds of programs the planners seem to be in my opinion the most versatile professional group in the world
They seem to be able to do anything that happens to be brought before them.
I've always told some of the people who work for us, we never say no to a project.
We'll say yes first and then we'll go about doing it and we'll find we're resourceful enough to figure out how to do it.

this is this we had moved from as you can remember some of the urban beautification programs the open space programs that you can recall the multitude of federal grants that were offered for community for community development and it was really ironic at two and funny at the time the planners became known by various titles depending on what program was in we had open space specialists we had
urban renewal specialist, and we had urban beautification specialist, and CRP specialist, as it came to be known.
But anyway, we had moved through collecting all the socioeconomic type data from the city and ready to start pulling together the pieces of comprehensive plan.
One of the problems that we had, and fortunately for me, working under Mrs. Cunningham and coming up here as I did,
He left me with some real good feelings about Mr. Anderson, who was at that time the director of planning.
And although the Community Road Program was not under his direct control, it did...
I did make the effort when I got here to personally get to know Mr. Anderson better and to start working with his staff because I knew that my job in developing a land use plan outside
the auspices of the Department of Planning would be almost impossible.
I needed that kind of close cooperation.
And that's one of the first things I set out doing.

And working with some of the staff members, Mr. Larry Winger, who's the chief planner now, basically the director of planning now, and Mr. Ogatz and several other people, because they had the, not only they had some of the resources, the mapping resources that we needed, but they had some of the,
local expertise that we needed on what, in their opinion, was going to happen to some of the developable lands in our community.
Unfortunately, the direction that the Community Renewal Program was taking as far as planning was concerned was not the direction that our former city manager, Mr. Townsend, wanted it to go.
The Community Renewal Program studies and a lot of staff members
began raising very controversial type of issues that only could be resolved through council, doing a lot of soul searching and developing some policies.
And these kinds of policy questions is what I gather in the past had never been confronted with the council.
Historically, planning
and the city of Corpus Christi had taken a back burner since the formulation and adoption of the comprehensive plan prepared in 1958 by Harlan Bartholomew and Associates.
That plan was sponsored, and I mean by sponsored, paid for by the Chamber of Commerce's Area Development Committee.
However, I suppose at that time that there was enough
good working relationships between the chamber and the cities and the county, that when the plan was brought before our governmental jurisdictions, that it was endorsed.
That is the only plan that's been adopted, comprehensive plan, for the city of Ropes Christi.
The community road program, realizing what we needed was a new plan, began working towards that direction.

1963, 1964, this area, under the leadership of William Anderson and several people at the State Department of Highways, and under the federal guidelines of the 1962 Federal Highway Act, developed the first, as I've been told, comprehensive transportation planning study.
which was published ultimately in 63 and 64.

And this was an effort that culminated from the work of not only the city of Corpus Christi, but the State Highway Department and also Nueces County, which Nueces County and Corpus at that time constituted the urbanized area.
And I think the Navigation District.
The Navigation District also was involved.
The plan, although it was published in 63 and 64,
and what was the title, a transportation plan, really became our second approved comprehensive plan for the urbanized area.
Because you cannot do transportation planning very effectively and ignore the other elements of a comprehensive plan.
And so as far as the planning,
of the preparation of the transportation plan went, it included every single element of a comprehensive plan.
It was just labeled the transportation plan.
It became the tool for carrying out planning in the Corpus area.
To give you an idea how anti-planning, I think, the community became, in 1967, 68, Harlem Athalamian Associates were brought back to Corpus, also under the
Area Development Committee of the Chamber of Commerce to update their 1958 plan.
This is it right in front of you.
Which, you know, after ten years it needed to be updated.
According to Anderson, the first plan had been built out and it had, in fact, come into reality so that the community needed another plan to go forward into the future.
That's true.

And I think if you go back through the 1958 plan, you'll find that the majority of significant recommendations for physical improvements and growth, the type of growth in our community, were followed.
Although there were a few isolated projects that were extremely controversial.
As soon as we have the harbor bridge,
connecting our North Beach to our mainland.
That was very controversial.
The connection itself wasn't controversial.
We knew we needed that.
But there was a lot of controversy over whether it should be a bridge or should it be a tunnel.
And it's my understanding and recollection from just talking with Anderson that the former mayor, or the mayor at that time, was really interested in having a tunnel.
I mean, he wanted a tunnel.
And he also owned a lot of property over there.
I don't know if those two were related, but he felt that the tunnel was the best means.
And when he was outvoted as far as going for a tunnel or a high bridge, he resigned his office to mayor.
And that's how controversial that project was.
That's pretty controversial.
But nevertheless, you're correct.
The plan had outlived its usefulness.
Most of the projects that were recommended in it were accomplished or were well underway of being accomplished.
And there was a definite need for an update or a new plan covering another 20-year plan, period.
So with that kind of background, you know, the Area Development Committee embarked upon another update using the same associates.
And paid for in the same way?
Paid for in the same way.
Well, I'm not sure where all the money came from.
It may even be that the City of Corpus Christi put some money into it, but I don't think so.
I think it was an Area Development Committee plan.
And the Area Development Committee, I shouldn't say Area Development Committee Plan.
They don't call it their plan.
It's a plan for the community.
They didn't want that kind of label on it.
But I believe the plan was completed and it was done, as well as the first one was done.
And it was very reasonable.
It was implementable.
There were some sections of the plan
in my opinion, were really off the wall.
And I think it created a lot of problems for the consultants in that they had gone, they had some fun with the project after they were through with the basic report.

And they put together a separate report called Offshore Highway Proposals, where they intended to build a major transportation facility leading from the Cayo de Oso Bay to the, you know, traversing the Corpus Christi Bay and back into downtown.
It was an alternate route into downtown.

I've got to remember that this is prior to the strong environmentals and there was also very pie in the sky type of planning and it was never well received either and I don't know how much that particular proposal went in discrediting the whole report but I think there was some problems at the time when the plan was finally brought before

presented to the city council and i think there was some some jealousies that it wasn't a plan that was commissioned by their own city council and developed under their direction that it was commissioned by someone outside them and they just did not want to adopt it and they didn't ever since that time any other document that has come before the council
that was comprehensive in nature, that required some sort of endorsement, has been endorsed by concept alone.
And this is basically what this means.
It gives a councilman an out, not to follow any specific policy recommendations or to achieve any kind of quantifiable objectives.
just endorsed in concept alone.
And that includes the Bayfront development plans that have been developed over the past.
That includes some of the area or neighborhood plans that we have developed.
So basically, we just use these plans as conceptual guides.
Now, I'll leave it up to you to determine how effective that is to a planner.
You can't go back to a city council with this as a conceptual guide and say, this is what we need to do, this is what we talked about doing two years ago, because it doesn't have the importance.
I say this because the transportation plan is not conceptually improved.
It is adopted.
It is project specific.
It is also long range.
And the reason it is adopted officially

that is a requirement when the 1962 federal rate highway act was passed the department of transportation the secretary to the department of transportation was given sole authority to withhold any federal funding for highway improvements if he determined in his own opinion that the urbanized area didn't develop these projects quote within the framework
of a planning process that was both comprehensive and developed cooperative among local area governments, and that it was coordinated with all other planning functions.

And with that kind of sign-off required in order to continue receiving urban systems funds for highway improvements, that left little question for what kind of approval city council had to give to it.
Since that time, we have been using the tool of approving a master transportation plan for this area as our way of addressing other comprehensive planning needs.
What do you mean by that?
I mean that we happen to include in our transportation plan a land use element.
we have to include in our transportation plan sections dealing with various utilities.
